                title="Physical laws"
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physical_laws">physical laws</a> that describe the relationship between the <a title="Motion"
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motion">motion</a> of an object and the <a title="Force"
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Force">forces</a> acting on it. These laws, which provide the basis for <b>Newtonian mechanics</b>, can be paraphrased as follows:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>A body remains at rest, or in motion at a constant speed in a straight line, except insofar as it is acted upon by a force.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>At any instant of time, the net force on a body is equal to the body's <a title="Acceleration"
                        href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acceleration">acceleration</a> multiplied by its mass or, equivalently, the rate at which the body's <a title="Momentum"
                        href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Momentum">momentum</a> is changing with time.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
